This article aims to create a complete list of [[CFLAGS]] which are considered "safe" for each given processor. These are the settings you should use if you are unsure which CFLAGS your processor needs.

== Finding your CPU ==
To identify the model of your CPU, you can look inside {{Path|/proc/cpuinfo}} for the "cpu family" and "model" numbers like so:
{{Cmd|grep -m1 -A3 "vendor_id" /proc/cpuinfo}}

Once you find this information, you can then match your CPU to one listed on this page in order to find out the suggested "safe" CFLAGS.

==x86/amd64==

=== Intel ===

==== Core i5/i7 ====
<pre>
vendor_id	: GenuineIntel
cpu family	: 6
model		: 42
model name	: Intel(R) Core(TM) i5-2400 CPU @ 3.10GHz
</pre>
{{File|/etc/portage/make.conf||<pre>
CHOST="x86_64-pc-linux-gnu"
CFLAGS="-march=corei7 -O2 -pipe"
CXXFLAGS="${CFLAGS}"
</pre>}}
{{Note|corei7 march support was introduced only as of gcc-4.6.  If you have an earlier version of GCC, use <pre>CFLAGS="-march=native -O2 -pipe"</pre>}}

==== Core 2 Duo ====
<pre>
vendor_id       : GenuineIntel
cpu family      : 6
model           : 15
model name      : Intel(R) Core(TM)2 Duo CPU     T7500  @ 2.20GHz
</pre>
{{File|/etc/portage/make.conf||<pre>
CHOST="x86_64-pc-linux-gnu"
CFLAGS="-march=core2 -O2 -pipe"
CXXFLAGS="${CFLAGS}"
</pre>}}

==== Pentium M (Centrino) ====
<pre>
vendor_id	: GenuineIntel
cpu family	: 6
model		: 13
model name	: Intel(R) Pentium(R) M processor 2.13GHz
</pre>
{{File|/etc/portage/make.conf||<pre>
CHOST="i686-pc-linux-gnu"
CFLAGS="-O2 -march=pentium-m -pipe -fomit-frame-pointer"
CXXFLAGS="${CFLAGS}"
</pre>}}
{{Note|1=When compiling gcc:4.6, switch to <pre>CFLAGS="-O2 -march=i686 -pipe -fomit-frame-pointer"</pre> on this specific package, see https://bugs.gentoo.org/show_bug.cgi?id=411333}}

